elements.content: Three novel coordination polymers containing dimeric d10 metal units, [Cd(2,3-Pydc)(H2O)2] n (1), [Zn(2,3-Pydc)(H2O)2] n (2), and {[La2Zn3(2,3-Pydc)6(H2O)6]·4H2O} n (3), have been synthesized by hydrothermal reaction of pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid (2,3-Pydc) with d10 metal oxides at a suitable temperature. Complex 1 is a one-dimensional (1D) ladder coordination polymer containing a dimeric Cd2O8N2 unit. Complex 2 forms a two-dimensional (2D) layer built from a unique Zn2O8N2 unit, in which each pair of Zn(II) ions are bridged by two water molecules. Complex 3 is a 2D heterometallic framework by 1D chain linked by Zn(2,3-Pydc) units, where the 1D chain is constructed via dimeric La2O16 units. The photoluminescent studies show that complex 2 illustrates an emission at 417 nm (λex = 363 nm).

Introduction

The construction of metal-organic coordination polymers is a rapidly growing field due to their intriguing potential applications, such as catalysis, magnetism, electronic and chemical separation. The molecular building block (MBB) approach has been introduced as a suitable method to design and construct these kinds of materials. Metal-ligand-directed assembly based on the MBB method has shown promise to the rational design and construction of these functional materials. Metal ions can be preselected so as to impart various functional properties or predictable coordination geometries. Polydentate organic ligands can be also selected for their diversity in the coordination modes. Many of these hybrid materials have been synthesized and characterized by rational selection of suitable ligands. Among the various ligands, multidentate N- or O-donor ligands, such as pyridine or imidazole (di)carboxylic acids, have drawn extensive attention in the construction of coordination polymer or metal-organic frameworks (MOF). For example, pyridine or imidazole dicarboxylic ligands, including pyridine-2,6-, 2,5- or 3,4-dicarboxylic and imidazole-3,4-dicarboxylic acids, have been extensively employed in the construction of such metal-organic frameworks. Compared with other pyridine-dicarboxylic acids, pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid (2,3-Pydc) is rarely used as a linkage ligand. It is probably due to the following reasons. First, it often behaves like picolinic acid, acting as a chelating bidentate ligand through the nitrogen atom and one oxygen atom of the carboxylic group in ortho position, and the second carboxyl group remains idle. Second, it prefers decarboxylation of the carboxylic group in the ortho position and transforms to nicotinic acid.

elements.content: Synthesis. These three complexes, [Cd(2,3-Pydc)(H2O)2] n (1), [Zn(2,3-Pydc)(H2O)2] n (2), and {[La2Zn3(2,3-Pydc)6(H2O)6]·4H2O} n (3), were all prepared through the hydrothermal reaction. As mentioned in the Introduction, the last products of pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid and metal oxides are sensitive to the hydrothermal temperature. Reactions of ZnO and pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid at different temperatures have been studied, and some interesting phenomena are found. When the temperature is 160 °C, pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid in situ decarboxylates and transforms to nicotinic acid. Zn(nicotinate)2(H2O)4 was obtained as the final product (see Figure S1 of the Supporting Information), which has been reported by Wang et al. Similar decomposition behaviors have been observed by Chen and Wood et al. If the temperature is lower (80 °C), a mononuclear complex, Zn(2,3-PydcH)2(H2O)2, was the only product (see Figure S2 of the Supporting Information), where pyridine 2,3-dicarboxylic acid behaves like picolinic acid and the carboxyl group of the meta position remains idle. So the middle temperature (120 °C) is selected. Fortunately, pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid neither decarboxlates nor becomes monodentate, and three coordination polymers based on dimeric subunits were obtained. Interestingly, although pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid and the mixed metal oxides (La2O3 and CdO for 1, ZnO and CdO for 2, and La2O3 and ZnO for 3) are used as the starting materials, only one heterometal coordination polymer (3) is obtained. When the corresponding metal oxides are used (CdO for 1 and ZnO for 2), the final products (1 and 2) can be also generated. However, their crystallinity is too poor to use for X-ray analysis. The facts may imply that there exists a competitive reaction in the process of crystal growth of this system.

The crystal analysis on complex 1 reveals that it is a one-dimensional (1D) ladder coordination polymer containing Cd2O8N2 units with 2,3-Pydc as the bridge ligands. As shown in Figure a, the Cd ion is in a distorted octahedral geometry and coordinated by one nitrogen atom, three carboxylate O atoms from three 2,3-Pydc ligands, and two water molecules. Each pair of Cd ions is bridged by two carboxylate O atoms to form a Cd2O8N2 unit. These dimeric Cd2 units feature a 1D ladder along the c axis interconnected via pyridine-dicarboxylate ligands (as illustrated in Figure b). The adjacent chains are further aggregated into a three-dimension (3D) network through the hydrogen bonds between the water molecules and carboxylate oxygen atoms. As shown in Figures c and S3 (Supporting Information), the neighboring chains in one row are antiparallel.

elements.content: [Zn(2,3-Pydc)(H 2 O) 2 ] n (2). Complex 2 is a two-dimensional (2D) layer built from Zn2O8N2 units interconnected by 2,3-Pydc ligands. The Zn ion is coordinated by one N, two carboxylate O, and three water molecules to form a distorted octahedral geometry. The O1W has a bond valence sum of 0.511, suggesting that O1W is a coordinated water molecule. This result is consistent with the charge balance consideration. Interestingly, two water molecules (O1W and O1Wb) link two Zn ions as bridges to create a novel Zn2O8N2 unit, which is different from the dimeric Cd2O8N2 in complex 1 (Figure a). To the best of our knowledge, it is the first example of transition metal polymer containing a dimeric (Zn−H2O)2 unit as a core. The Zn2O8N2 dimeric units in complex 2 are bridged by pyridine-carboxylate to form a layer along the bc plane, as illustrated in Figure b. Within the layer, four dimeric Zn2O8N2 units construct a rhombic grid with a cavity dimension of 8.84 × 15.42 Å2. A similar topology has been reported recently, while the bridges in dimeric M2O x units are all oxygen atoms of corresponding ligands. Such 2D layers are held together via O−H···O hydrogen interactions, where the distance between the adjacent layers is 5.41 Å (based on the distances of Zn).

Complex 3 is a 2D framework containing 1D chains constructed via dimeric La2O16 units with Zn(2,3-Pydc) units as the bridge spacer. The symmetrical unit in 3 has a nine-coordinated lanthanide center and two types of zinc centers (shown in Figure a). The lanthanide ion is coordinated by seven oxygen atoms from six carboxlate groups and two O atoms from water molecules. Each pair of La(III) ions are bridged by two O atoms of carboxlate (O5 and O52) to form a dimeric La2O16 unit. The dimeric La2O16 units further form a zigzag chain with two carboxlate groups of bidentate bridging mode along the a axis. The Zn(2) ion is six-coordinated by four 2,3-Pydc ligands and links the lanthanide chains as a bridge, as shown in Figures b and S4 (Supporting Information), to make the 1D chain further extend into the 2D layer framework. The distance of the adjacent chains is 1.26 nm. Zn(3) ions are beside the 1D lanthanide oxide chain alternately, sharing oxygen atoms, and at the same time they are coordinated with two pyridine N atoms, two single dentate oxygen atoms, and one water molecule.

The centroid−centroid distance (3.641 Å), planar-to-planar distance (3.418 Å), and displacement angle (20.13°) between two pyridine rings of neighboring layers suggest strong π−π interactions. elements.content: Thermogravimetry (TG). The chemical formulas of complexes of 1−3 are confirmed by the results of element analysis. Thermogravimetric analysis on these three crystalline samples was carried out and results are given in Figures S6−S8 of the Supporting Information. The TG curves of complex 1 show that the 1D coordination polymer is stable up to 130 °C in air and then decomposes till 200 °C with a weight loss of 11.13% (calcd 11.49%) attributed to the dehydration of the two coordinated water molecules. The weight loss occurring between 270 and 800 °C corresponds to decomposition of pyridine-dicarboxylate. The final residual is 42.16%, which is CdO based on PXRD studies (calcd 40.95%). The temperature from 160 to 270 °C indicates a course of loss of water molecules in complex 2. The value of weight loss (12.91%) is close to the calculated value (13.52%). The decomposition of ligand is similar to complex 1, and ZnO is residual based on PXRD studies (calcd 30.54%, found 33.65%). The temperature of water loss in complex 2 is higher than that of 1, perhaps due to the difference of the bond energy of metal ions and the porosity of their structures. The TG of complex 3 is different from the forenamed complexes. The complex 3 is unstable in air and begins to decompose at room temperature. Through the decomposition of water molecules and ligands, the final products are La2O3 and ZnO based on PXRD studies (calcd 34.65%, found 33.95%).

elements.content: Photoluminescence. During the past few years, the photoluminescent properties of many d10 metal coordination polymers have been studied, and the studies reveal that their luminescence behaviors are closely associated with the central metal ions and the ligands coordinated with them. The photoluminescent properties of free 2,3-Pydc acid and complexes 1, 2, and 3 have been investigated in solid state at room temperature. Unfortunately, complexes 1 and 3 exhibit very weak emissions. The emission spectra of compound 2 and free 2,3-Pydc acid are illustrated in Figure . The free pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid ligand displays luminescence with an emission maximum at 470 nm (λ = 370 nm), which is attributed to the π* → n transition. Compared with the free ligand, the compound 2 shows different luminescent properties; it exhibits a broad emission at 417 nm when excited at 363 nm. The emission can be assigned to the ligand-to-metal charge transfer (LMCT), rather than the π* → n transition of the ligand. Similar LMCT has been reported in many metal−organic coordination polymers. A similar emission band at 436 nm for [Zn(PDB)] n and 452 nm for [Cd3(PDB)2(OH)2(H2O)2] n has been observed recently.

In summary, three novel d10 metal complexes of pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylate constructed by dimeric M2 units have been hydrothermally synthesized and characterized by EA, IR, and TG/DTA associated with single-crystal analysis. The photoluminescent behaviors of the three complexes have been also discussed. The metal−organic framework constructed by dimeric units is little. We believe that many new functional inorganic−organic hybrids will be designed and synthesized as candidates for advanced materials.

elements.content: Materials and Measurements:  All the starting materials were purchased from commercial sources and used without further purification. The IR spectra were recorded from KBr pellets at a range of 400−4000 cm-1 on a Nicolet 5700 FTIR spectrometer with a spectral resolution of 4.00 cm-1. Thermogravimetric studies were carried out on a NETZSCH STA 449C at a heating rate 20 K/min in air. The elemental analysis data were obtained from a Perkin-Elmer 240B elemental analyzer. The powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) patterns of the decomposition products were obtained with a Shimadzu XRD-6000 diffractometer with Cu Kα 1 radiation (λ = 1.540 56 Å) at 30 kV and 30 mA at the scan speed of (2θ) 4°/min. Excitation and emission spectra in solid state were examined with a HITACHI F-4500 fluorescence spectrophotometer equipped with a xenon lamp as the excitation source in the range of 200−550 nm.

La2O3 (0.2 mmol), CdO (0.4 mmol), and pyridine-2,3-dicarboxylic acid (1.0 mmol) were added into 10 mL of water and stirred for 5 min in air, then transferred to a closed container. After reacting at 120 °C for 3 days, the mixture was cooled to room temperature at a rate of 5 °C/h. Colorless crystals suitable for X-ray analysis were obtained. Elemental analysis. cln_elements.content: Thermogravimetry (TG). The chemical formulas of complexes of 1−3 are confirmed by the results of element analysis. Thermogravimetric analysis on these three crystalline samples was carried out and results are given in Figures S6−S8 of the Supporting Information. The TG curves of complex 1 show that the 1D coordination polymer is stable up to 130 °C in air and then decomposes till 200 °C with a weight loss of 11.13% (calcd 11.49%) attributed to the dehydration of the two coordinated water molecules. The weight loss occurring between 270 and 800 °C corresponds to decomposition of pyridine-dicarboxylate. The final residual is 42.16%, which is CdO based on PXRD studies (calcd 40.95%). The temperature from 160 to 270 °C indicates a course of loss of water molecules in complex 2. The value of weight loss (12.91%) is close to the calculated value (13.52%). The decomposition of ligand is similar to complex 1, and ZnO is residual based on PXRD studies (calcd 30.54%, found 33.65%). The temperature of water loss in complex 2 is higher than that of 1, perhaps due to the difference of the bond energy of metal ions and the porosity of their structures. The TG of complex 3 is different from the forenamed complexes. The complex 3 is unstable in air and begins to decompose at room temperature. Through the decomposition of water molecules and ligands, the final products are La2O3 and ZnO based on PXRD studies (calcd 34.65%, found 33.95%).
